description:
## Summary

Replace the hand-rolled BM25 search implementation in `mcp-server/src/search/index.ts` (~300 lines) with MiniSearch (npm: `minisearch`, ~23 KB gzipped, 0 dependencies, TypeScript-native, BM25+ scoring).

## Motivation

The current implementation works but is custom code that must be maintained for:
- BM25 scoring with field weights
- Inverted index construction
- Serialize/deserialize for pre-bundling
- Stopword removal, suffix stripping, camelCase splitting

MiniSearch provides all of this out of the box with a well-tested, actively maintained library (571k weekly downloads, 5.8k GitHub stars, last published Sep 2025). The migration would eliminate ~200 lines of hand-rolled search code while improving scoring quality (BM25+ vs basic BM25).

## Current Architecture

### Files
- **`mcp-server/src/search/index.ts`** (291 lines) — tokenizer, buildIndex, search, serializeIndex, deserializeIndex
- **`mcp-server/src/search/index.test.ts`** (163 lines) — 25 tests covering tokenize, buildIndex, search, roundtrip serialization

### Exports consumed by other modules
- \`tokenize(text: string): string[]\` — used only internally within search module
- \`buildIndex(skills: Map<string, Skill>): SearchIndex\` — called by DevLoader, ProdLoader, bundle.ts
- \`search(index, query, options?, skills?): SearchResult[]\` — called by DevLoader, ProdLoader
- \`serializeIndex(index: SearchIndex): SerializedSearchIndex\` — called by bundle.ts
- \`deserializeIndex(data: SerializedSearchIndex): SearchIndex\` — called by ProdLoader
- \`SearchIndex\` interface — used by DevLoader (field type), ProdLoader (field type)
- \`SerializedSearchIndex\` interface — used by ProdLoader (BundleV2 type), bundle.ts
- \`SearchResult\` interface — used by Loader interface, handler.ts response formatting

### Current features
1. **BM25 scoring** with k1=1.2, b=0.75
2. **Field weights**: name (3x), description (2x), tags (2x), sectionHeadings (1.5x), body (1x)
3. **Custom tokenizer**: camelCase splitting, stopword removal, suffix stripping (-ing, -tion, -ness, -ment)
4. **Section-level term tracking**: \`sectionTerms\` maps docName → sectionHeading → Set<term>, used to populate \`matchingSections\` in SearchResult
5. **Post-search filtering**: by skillType, category, source
6. **Serialization roundtrip**: serializeIndex converts Maps/Sets to Records/arrays for JSON, deserializeIndex restores them
7. **Router exclusion**: skills with skillType === 'router' are excluded from the index

## MiniSearch API Mapping

### Installation
\`\`\`bash
pnpm add minisearch
\`\`\`

### Constructor (replaces buildIndex)
\`\`\`typescript
import MiniSearch from 'minisearch';

const miniSearch = new MiniSearch<Skill>({
  fields: ['name', 'description', 'tags', 'sectionHeadings', 'body'],
  storeFields: ['name', 'description', 'skillType', 'source', 'category'],
  tokenize: axiomTokenize,  // our existing tokenize function
  searchOptions: {
    boost: { name: 3, description: 2, tags: 2, sectionHeadings: 1.5, body: 1 },
    bm25: { k: 1.2, b: 0.75 },
  },
});
\`\`\`

### Adding documents (replaces the for-loop in buildIndex)
\`\`\`typescript
for (const [name, skill] of skills) {
  if (skill.skillType === 'router') continue;
  miniSearch.add({
    id: name,
    name: skill.name.replace(/[-_]/g, ' '),
    description: skill.description,
    tags: skill.tags.join(' '),
    sectionHeadings: skill.sections.map(s => s.heading).join(' '),
    body: skill.content,
  });
}
\`\`\`

### Search (replaces search function)
\`\`\`typescript
const results = miniSearch.search(query, {
  filter: (result) => {
    if (options?.skillType && result.skillType !== options.skillType) return false;
    if (options?.category && result.category !== options.category) return false;
    if (options?.source && result.source !== options.source) return false;
    return true;
  },
});
// result.match provides { [term]: string[] } — which fields matched
\`\`\`

### Serialization (replaces serializeIndex/deserializeIndex)
\`\`\`typescript
// Serialize for bundle
const serialized = JSON.stringify(miniSearch);

// Deserialize from bundle (must pass same options)
const restored = MiniSearch.loadJSON(serialized, {
  fields: ['name', 'description', 'tags', 'sectionHeadings', 'body'],
  storeFields: ['name', 'description', 'skillType', 'source', 'category'],
  tokenize: axiomTokenize,
});
\`\`\`

## Gap: Section-Level Term Tracking

MiniSearch's \`result.match\` tells you which **fields** matched (e.g., \`{ "concurrency": ["name", "body"] }\`) but NOT which **sections within the body** matched. The current implementation maintains a parallel \`sectionTerms\` data structure for this.

### Recommended approach
Keep a thin wrapper that builds \`sectionTerms\` alongside the MiniSearch index. This is ~30 lines:

\`\`\`typescript
// Built alongside MiniSearch index, serialized separately
const sectionTerms = new Map<string, Map<string, Set<string>>>();

for (const [name, skill] of skills) {
  if (skill.skillType === 'router') continue;
  const docSections = new Map<string, Set<string>>();
  for (const section of skill.sections) {
    const lines = skill.content.split('\\n').slice(section.startLine, section.endLine + 1);
    const sectionText = section.heading + ' ' + lines.join(' ');
    docSections.set(section.heading, new Set(axiomTokenize(sectionText)));
  }
  sectionTerms.set(name, docSections);
}
\`\`\`

Then during search, map query terms to matching sections:

\`\`\`typescript
for (const result of miniSearchResults) {
  const docSections = sectionTerms.get(result.id);
  const matched = new Set<string>();
  if (docSections) {
    for (const term of queryTerms) {
      for (const [heading, terms] of docSections) {
        if (terms.has(term)) matched.add(heading);
      }
    }
  }
  // result.matchingSections = Array.from(matched);
}
\`\`\`

### Alternative (future consideration)
Model each section as a separate MiniSearch document with a parent reference. This would let MiniSearch handle section matching natively but adds complexity for 80 documents.

## Implementation Plan

### Step 1: Add dependency
- \`pnpm add minisearch\` in mcp-server
- Verify it's ESM-compatible with the existing module setup (Node16 moduleResolution)

### Step 2: Create new search module
- Keep \`tokenize()\` function as-is (it becomes the custom tokenizer passed to MiniSearch)
- Replace \`buildIndex()\` with MiniSearch constructor + document addition + sectionTerms side-build
- Replace \`search()\` with MiniSearch.search() + filter + sectionTerms lookup
- Replace \`serializeIndex()\` with \`JSON.stringify(miniSearch)\` + sectionTerms serialization
- Replace \`deserializeIndex()\` with \`MiniSearch.loadJSON()\` + sectionTerms deserialization

### Step 3: Preserve the public API
The \`SearchIndex\` type changes from a custom interface to an opaque wrapper:

\`\`\`typescript
export interface SearchIndex {
  miniSearch: MiniSearch;
  sectionTerms: Map<string, Map<string, Set<string>>>;
  docCount: number;
}
\`\`\`

All callers (DevLoader, ProdLoader, bundle.ts) use \`buildIndex\`, \`search\`, \`serializeIndex\`, \`deserializeIndex\` — these function signatures stay the same. The change is internal only.

### Step 4: Update SerializedSearchIndex
\`\`\`typescript
export interface SerializedSearchIndex {
  miniSearchJSON: string;  // JSON.stringify(miniSearch) output
  sectionTerms: Record<string, Record<string, string[]>>;
  docCount: number;
}
\`\`\`

### Step 5: Update tests
- \`tokenize\` tests: unchanged (function stays the same)
- \`buildIndex\` tests: update to verify MiniSearch-backed index has correct docCount
- \`search\` tests: same assertions (ranked results, filtering, section matching)
- Roundtrip test: verify serialize → deserialize → search produces identical results
- Add test: verify MiniSearch options (fields, boost, tokenizer) are consistent between build and load

### Step 6: Verify bundle workflow
- \`npm run build\` — TypeScript compiles
- \`npm run build:bundle\` — bundle.json generates with MiniSearch serialized index
- Verify bundle.json size hasn't changed dramatically
- Test loading bundle in ProdLoader

## Files Modified

| File | Change |
|------|--------|
| \`mcp-server/package.json\` | Add \`minisearch\` dependency |
| \`mcp-server/src/search/index.ts\` | Replace internals with MiniSearch, keep public API |
| \`mcp-server/src/search/index.test.ts\` | Update buildIndex/search tests, add MiniSearch-specific tests |
| \`mcp-server/src/loader/prod-loader.ts\` | No change (uses same public API) |
| \`mcp-server/src/loader/dev-loader.ts\` | No change (uses same public API) |
| \`mcp-server/src/scripts/bundle.ts\` | No change (uses same public API) |
| \`mcp-server/src/tools/handler.ts\` | No change (uses SearchResult, unchanged) |

## Risks

1. **Bundle size increase**: MiniSearch adds ~23 KB gzipped. The bundle.json serialized index format will change (MiniSearch's internal format vs current custom format). Need to verify total bundle.json size.
2. **Scoring differences**: BM25+ (MiniSearch) vs BM25 (current) may produce slightly different ranking for the same query. BM25+ adds a delta parameter that prevents zero scores for very long documents. This should improve results, not regress them.
3. **Serialization format change**: Existing bundle.json files won't be compatible. The bundle is regenerated on each \`npm run build:bundle\`, so this is only a concern if someone has cached an old bundle.
4. **MiniSearch loadJSON requires same options**: The fields, tokenizer, and other options passed to \`MiniSearch.loadJSON()\` must exactly match those used during index creation. This is a common gotcha — extract options into a shared constant.

## Verification

1. \`npm test\` — all search tests pass with same assertions
2. \`npm run build\` — TypeScript compiles cleanly
3. \`npm run build:bundle\` — bundle generates, verify size
4. Manual test: search for "Sendable", "NavigationStack", "data race" — verify results match or improve vs current
5. Verify \`axiom_search_skills\` MCP tool returns same quality results

## Research Sources

- MiniSearch npm: https://www.npmjs.com/package/minisearch (v7.2.0, 571k weekly downloads)
- MiniSearch GitHub: https://github.com/lucaong/minisearch (5.8k stars)
- MiniSearch docs: https://lucaong.github.io/minisearch/
- Alternatives evaluated and rejected: Orama (2.2 MB, overkill), FlexSearch (not BM25, unstable API), Lunr.js (abandoned, TF-IDF), wink-bm25 (abandoned, no TS), Fuse.js (fuzzy, not keyword search)
